attributes.description: Publicly shared information about this project, including Registered study protocol versions, etc.

q1.value: Developing Reward-Enhanced ERP (RE-ERP) as a novel treatment for tic disorders: R33

q2.value: Kevin J. Black, Kimberly Sirl, John Piacentini, Melanie VanDyke

q3.value: We propose to modify exposure and response prevention (ERP) by adding automated, in-session immediate rewards for brief tic-free periods, or reward-enhanced ERP (RE-ERP). The R33 phase tests whether target engagement (improvement in tic suppression efficacy) correlates with clinical improvement over the course of treatment. This phase is constructed as a randomized trial with noncontingent reward (NCR) as a control arm for standard RE-ERP, which uses differential reinforcement of other (tic-free) behavior (DRO).

q4.value: Clinical improvement will correlate with improvement in within-session, immediately rewarded tic suppression ability.

q5.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: For studies that involve human subjects, they will not know the treatment group to which they have been assigned.
Personnel who analyze the data collected from the study are not aware of the treatment applied to any given group.
Personnel who interact directly with the study subjects (either human or non-human subjects) will not be aware of the assigned treatments. (Commonly known as “double blind”)

q7.value: Video-based tic rating from before and after RE-ERP will be done after randomizing the order of the videos so that the rater is blind to whether the video was recorded before or after treatment. Other data analyses are not blind to order effects.

question.value: The primary analysis involves within-subject comparison of clinical improvement and changes in immediately rewarded tic suppression efficacy over the course of treatment. The R33 study also involves a randomized allocation study of standard RE-ERP (DRO) vs. RE-ERP with NCR, but is not powered as an efficacy study.

q9.value:
The treatment (DRO vs. NCR) will be assigned randomly. Subjects will be sequentially randomized using minimization software [9] to allocate ADHD and OCD symptom severity and medication treatment status as nearly equally between groups as possible [10]. ADHD status will be defined by a median split in ADHD Rating Scale score based on our data from an ongoing tic study [11] (current median = 14, n = 41, but we may update this prior to enrolling the first subject). OCD status will be defined by diagnosis at the screening/baseline visit. Medication status will be defined by a binary variable for each of 5 medication classes: antipsychotics, α2 agonists, stimulants, SSRIs, and other psychotropics. Based on expected effects on attention and reward, ADHD, antipsychotics, α2 agonists and stimulants will be weighted twice as strongly as the other classes in the minimization program. Minimization will be performed with a “biased coin flip” (weight 0.8), rather than deterministically. Residual mismatches on these categories will also be addressed in analysis (see next section).
  The current plan is to use OxMaR software [9] for minimization, but before enrollment starts a different program with similar functionality, such as MinimPy, may be substituted.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: Participants are recruited as a convenience sample by referral and advertising. They meet inclusion and exclusion criteria listed on page 9 of the attached file ("Page 72" in the footer). Participants are paid $125 for each of two visits (screening/baseline and post-treatment). Planned timeline: see attached document. Tic suppression efficacy is defined for the two in-person visits based on expert scoring of the videos blind to time point (pre- vs post-treatment). Tic suppression efficacy between these visits is based on a parent noting tics on free-to-tic videos and in subsequent treatment sessions.

q13.value: The R33 phase is designed for screening 45 participants, with 36 completing treatment. If the study design for the active treatment does not change substantially from Aim 2, we will add the Aim 2 participants to the correlation analysis.

q14.value: The primary analysis will measure the correlation between the target (improvement in tic suppression efficacy E across treatment sessions, as a slope) and the change from start to end in YGTSS total tic score (ΔTTS). Assuming well-chosen covariates, this functions approximately as a simple Pearson correlation. The effect size detectable with 80% power, given N = 36 and α =.05, is rho = .39 (accounting for 15.2% of variance) [7,8].

question.value: Treatment arms: standard RE-ERP (DRO) and RE-ERP with NCR.

Tic suppression efficacy E, is based on the mean number of 10-second tic-free intervals per minute during a given RE-ERP session (S) and the mean number of 10-second tic-free intervals per minute during the most recent “free to tic, alone” video (A), as follows: E = (S − A) / (6 − A) (optionally multiplied by 100%). S and A range from 0.0 (ticcing at least every 10 s) to 6.0 (no tics). A suppression efficacy score of E = 0 means no suppression during the session, while a score of E = 100% occurs only with complete suppression during the session. If there are no tics in the “free to tic, alone” condition, the formula above does not work, and we will set E = 100% but track such data separately.
All other outcome measures are described on page 12 of the attached file (Page 75 in the footer). Measured predictors or covariates are described on p. 10 of the attached file.
See above for definition of E. See analysis section for use of slopes for analysis of within-treatment data, and for possible addition of significant covariates or factors.

The primary analysis will use a mixed (random effects) model, with slope of rewarded tic suppression ability E change over time as the independent variable, and ΔTTS, the change in the YGTSS total tic score from baseline, as the dependent variable. Depending on the results from the R61 analysis, the model of change in suppression ability over time used in the analysis may be altered (before collecting R33 data) from a linear model to a more general model (e.g. a parabolic or sigmoid model). 
  Baseline tic severity, age, sex, comorbidity (ADHD Rating Scale and CY-BOCS scores) and medication status (binary variables for each of 5 classes of common medications) will be added to the model if they explain a significant fraction of the variance in the primary outcome measure. As a check, key results will also be examined in subjects with no medication treatment and no diagnosis of ADHD or OCD (the most common comorbidities).
  The analysis will be repeated using only the pre- and post-treatment, expert-rated tic counts from the treatment session vs the free-to-tic, alone videos, all rated blind to time point.
  A similar analysis will use the change in the Modified Rush Video-Based Tic Rating Scale as the dependent variable rather than the ΔTTS; this analysis is important as the video ratings are blind to time point as well as to treatment allocation.
  The efficacy analysis (DRO vs. NCR) will use a similar model except that a comparison of group means is the primary analysis, with added covariates as mentioned. For this analysis, any subject who does not return for the post-treatment visit will be deemed to have a ΔTTS of zero, consistent with a last observation carried forward (LOCF) approach.

q20.value: As above: If a nonlinear model such as a sigmoid curve fits the data for course of improvement over time substantially better (by a model comparison F test, adjusting for the number of model parameters), we will substitute that for the linear analysis.

q21.value: p < .05 for each analysis above, one-tailed tests as we have directional hypotheses. The correlations of ΔTTS with change in parent-rated E during treatment, and with change in expert-rated E from before to after treatment, are each considered a primary analysis. Other analyses will be noted as secondary.

q22.value: Prior to analyses above, any score > 3 SD beyond the group mean will be removed from the analysis.

q23.value:
Between-visits correlational analysis: Any participant who has completed less than 4 weeks of RE-ERP treatment will be excluded, 
  Pre- vs post-treatment correlational analysis: Any participant who does not return for the post-treatment visit will be excluded.
  Group comparison: Any subject who does not return for the post-treatment visit will be deemed to have a ΔTTS of zero, consistent with a last observation carried forward (LOCF) approach.

q24.value:
* We will compare changes in YGTSS, CGI-I, PTQ and Rush video score data between groups by comparing group mean improvement after including significant factors or covariates as described for the primary analysis above. See also "Secondary Outcome Measures," p. 12 in the attached file (Page 75 in the footer).
* We will test for information about the mechanism of improvement; namely, whether clinical improvement correlates best to tic suppression, response inhibition more broadly, habituation to urge, or a change in self-efficacy (see Table on p. 9 of the attached file for these variables). Additional secondary analyses will examine predictive variables (such as whether improvement depends on treatment adherence or ADHD) and secondary outcome measures (such as whether BATS score or GTS-QoL scores improve with successful treatment).

q25.value:
See the attached files for any missing details. 
NOTE: After submission on 2020-02-14 (corresponding to the attached files), I noticed errors in the power section of the analysis plan (e.g. direction of expected change). I also realized that the attached document does not describe the analysis of the post- vs. pre-treatment, expert-rated tic suppression efficacy data. These errors have been corrected in this registration.
